<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ901231-0038</DOCNO><DOCID>901231-0038.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- AmeriFirst Bank:   Thrift Has 4th Period Loss,   Erasing Remaining Equity</HL><DATE>12/31/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 3</SO><CO>   AMRI</CO><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)EARNINGS (ERN)</IN><GV>TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)</GV><LP>   AmeriFirst Bank, already struggling to avoid seizure byfederal thrift regulators, reported a fourth-quarter loss of$129.9 million that wipes out its remaining equity.   The loss, which includes $86.7 million in loan-lossprovisions, amounts to $11.76 a share. A year ago, the thriftposted a fourth-quarter loss of $49.1 million, or $4.44 ashare.</LP><TEXT>   AmeriFirst didn't specify the size of its total reservesfor bad loans. But it said it increased the reserves afterthe Office of Thrift Supervision and auditors KPMG PeatMarwick reviewed its assets.   An AmeriFirst spokeswoman said the bank, which has beenoperating under strict supervision by the Office of ThriftSupervision since August, has proposed a plan to meet capitalstandards through an infusion of private capital by a groupincluding former Chairman M. Lee Pearce.   But the Miami bank now has a negative net worth of $81million, and Sally McIver, an analyst with SNL Securities inCharlottesville, Va., said that makes it a strong candidateto be seized by regulators.</TEXT></DOC>